== History ==
The shrine is traditionally said to have been founded in [[876]] (the 18th year of the {{ill|Jōgan era|ja|貞観|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Jōgan era|qq=}}). During the {{ill|Heian period|ja|平安時代|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Heian period|qq=}}, the area was coastal and formed a sandbar called "Suzaki." Thus, the shrine became known as "Hama-no-Miya" (Shrine of the Beach).

The exact date of the establishment of the {{ill|Inari Shrine|ja|稲荷神社|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Inari Shrine|qq=}} is unknown.

== Shrine Buildings and Grounds ==
The grounds include the {{ill|Miyamado Inari Shrine|ja|海山道稲荷神社|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Miyamado Inari Shrine|qq=}}, which surpasses the Shinmei Shrine in scale.

There are over 20 subsidiary {{ill|Inari shrines|ja|稲荷神社|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Inari shrines|qq=}}, a {{ill|Tenjin shrine|ja|天神社|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tenjin shrine|qq=}} housing Japan’s largest statue of {{ill|Sugawara no Michizane|ja|Sugawara no Michizane|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Sugawara no Michizane|qq=}}, and various monuments such as the Pen Mound, Eyeglass Mound, and Fox Mound.

== Festivals and Events ==
* festival: October 3–5
* Inari Grand Festival: April 8–9
* Fox Wedding Ceremony: Held on {{ill|Setsubun|ja|節分|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Setsubun|qq=}} (February), this purification ritual involves a mock wedding procession. Participants representing the bride and groom wear fox masks, and a "bean-throwing" event is also held.

== location ==
1-62 Miyamado Town, [[Yokkaichi]], [[Mie Prefecture]], Japan

== Access ==
* A short walk from [[Kintetsu Nagoya Line]]'s [[Miyamado Station]].

